and Sean Illing reveal how these changes have challenged democracy—often with unsettling effects. The Paradox of Democracy captures the deep connection between communication and political culture, from the ancient art of rhetoric and the revolutionary role of newspapers to liberal broadcast media and the toxic misinformation of the digital public sphere. With clear-eyed analysis, Gershberg and Illing show that our contemporary debates over media, populism, and cancel culture are not too different from democratic cultural experiences of the past. As we grapple with a fast-changing, hyper-digital world, they prove democracy is always perched precipitously on a razor’s edge, now as ever before.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aDemocracyxPhilosophy. 0aJournalismxPolitical aspects. 0aMass media and public opinion. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ademocracy, democratic government, free speech, freedom, journalism, media studies, journalists, history, historical context, communications, politics, political science, cultural study, rhetoric, newspapers, broadcast, television, news, misinformation, digital content, internet, populism, cancel culture, public opinion, philosophy, bias, biased, disruptions, fascism, liberal, liberalism, representation, governing ideas.1 aIlling, Sean, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226818900423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226818900/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles